data.content:
Your test works but uses generic `Assert.IsTrue` everywhere, which gives poor failure messages (just "expected True, got False"). MSTest 3.x+ has specialized collection assertions:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);                          // vs Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));         // ✅ this one is fine
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);                         // vs Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)
    Assert.Contains(users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin"), users); // or better:
}
```

**Full rewrite using modern APIs:**

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();

    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.IsNotNull(users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Your code | Modern assertion | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Says "collection was empty" on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Says "expected 3, got 5" on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(x)` | Says "value was null" on failure |

`HasCount(3, users)` already implies non-empty, so you can drop the separate emptiness check. The `All()` predicate has no built-in equivalent, so `Assert.IsTrue` is appropriate there.
